node.title: Crying for help: 'It feels like no one is listening'
node.description: It took four referrals and a confession she was harming herself for Quinn to finally be accepted to a DHB mental health service. But although she is now in the system, the 14 year old is still not…

node.title: House January 6 committee to vote on contempt charges against Mark Meadows
node.description: The former Trump chief of staff initially was "engaging" with the committee but has since pulled involvement.

node.title: Vicente Fernández, el rey de los machos y el desamor
node.description: Puede que el machismo encarnado por sus canciones se haya desgastado, pero su música seguirá siendo parte de las fibras sonoras de lo latinoamericano y lo latino en Estados Unidos.

node.title: The Bogus Bashing of Build Back Better
node.description: Beware of bad faith, bad logic and bad arithmetic.

node.title: California regulators propose raising fees on owners of rooftop solar systems.
node.description: The plan was welcomed by the state’s electric utilities while a solar industry association leader called it a “disaster.”

node.title: Manchin Casts Doubt on Quick Vote on Biden’s Social Policy Bill
node.description: The West Virginia Democrat said he still harbored serious concerns about the $2.2 trillion measure, potentially frustrating his party’s push to win Senate approval before Christmas.

node.title: Kentucky Tornadoes Followed Flash Floods, Ice Storm and a Covid Spike
node.description: Even before the catastrophic storm claimed dozens of lives, a state and its governor have been repeatedly tested.

node.title: Lawyers Clash Again Over Subpoena for Trump’s Financial Records
node.description: The long-running case dates back to an early 2019 House Oversight Committee demand to see years of the then-president’s financial data.

node.title: US Navy Begins Testing Wind-Powered, Sensor-Packed 'Sailboat Drone'
node.description: The new drone tests are part of an ongoing initiative by the Navy to integrate unmanned crafts into its existing fleet.

node.title: Former NFL Player Josh Bellamy Jailed for Receiving Over $1.2M in Fraudulent COVID Relief
node.description: Former NFL player Josh Bellamy used fraudulent documentation to receive $1.2 million in PPP loans, which he admitted to using for personal reasons.

node.title: Anne Sacoolas, U.S. Diplomat's Wife, to Face British Court for Crash That Killed Harry Dunn
node.description: Sacoolas, accused of causing the 2019 accident that caused the death of 19-year-old Dunn in Britain, will reportedly see British court in some form in January.

node.title: Cris Collinsworth Criticized for Lauding 'Honesty' of Aaron Rodgers Following Vaccine Lie
node.description: "We have heard from the beginning of this entire season exactly what he thinks about everything," Collinsworth said.

node.title: SD Gov. Kristi Noem Wants Moment of Silence to Begin Each School Day, Hopes Kids Will Pray
node.description: The legislation said that the moment should not be seen as religious, but a statement from Noem's office said it's meant to protect prayer in schools.

node.title: Anjanette Young, Woman Handcuffed Naked in Botched Chicago Raid, to Get $2.9M From City
node.description: A Chicago City Council committee recommended a multimillion-dollar settlement for Anjanette Young, which the full council will consider on Wednesday.

node.title: 'Deplorable' lack of care for historic hospital sees threat of legal action against Chinese property developer
node.description: The NSW government says it will undertake urgent work to protect a historic disused hospital, and send the bill to the owner, a Chinese property developer.

node.title: Adelaide personal trainer banned from acting as dietitian over 'unsafe' diet plans
node.description: Norman Low is permanently banned from providing diet advice to clients after providing "inappropriate and unsafe plans to consumers which were fundamentally flawed, not backed by science, inappropriate, unsafe" and were not developed by a dietitian.

node.title: Snoop Dogg steps up for the Golden Globes, but where are all the other stars?
node.description: The only star to take to the stage for the 2022 Golden Globes nominations was rapper Snoop Dogg. Other stars have been eerily quiet.

node.title: Tasmania introduces vaccine mandate for childcare workers one day before border opens
node.description: Tasmanian Premier Peter Gutwein announces all childcare workers will have to be vaccinated against COVID-19, after pressure from the sector.

node.title: SA on track to further ease COVID-19 restrictions by the end of the year
node.description: South Australia will likely further ease its coronavirus restrictions between Christmas and New Year's Eve, but the emergence of the Omicron strain means the state may not be as free as previously proposed.

node.title: Biden warns Putin: Russia will pay 'terrible price' if it invades Ukraine
node.description: US President Joe Biden on Saturday said he told Russian President Vladimir Putin that Russia would pay "a terrible price" and face devastating economic consequences if it invaded Ukraine.

node.title: Promotion Sends Teachers Scrambling to Scoop Up Cash. Critics Give It an F.
node.description: Ten teachers in South Dakota competed for $5,000 in dollar bills to spend on classroom improvements. Critics called the event at a hockey game in Sioux Falls demeaning.

node.title: Farmers divided on what makes Australia's tastiest lamb, but 120,000 tasters can't be wrong
node.description: Selecting tasty, juicy and tender lamb is set to become easier with new grading standards, but the move is dividing the sheepmeat industry.

node.title: Nai-Ni Chen, Whose Dances Merged East and West, Dies at 62
node.description: Ms. Chen, who founded the Nai-Ni Chen Dance Company in 1988, died while swimming in Hawaii, where she was vacationing.

node.title: N.Y. Knicks Ticket Prices Quadruple For Tuesday's Potentially Historic Game
node.description: Some tickets are almost $15,000 apiece. The odds that Steph Curry will break a remarkable record Tuesday night are razor thin, but it could happen.

node.title: New Report Calls Colombian Police Actions During Protests a 'Massacre' Against Civilians
node.description: "Police acted with disproportionate use of force and went after the poorest people in the city," said attorney and human rights expert Carlos Negret.

node.title: China records first case of Omicron COVID variant
node.description: Health authorities in northern China's port city of Tianjin have detected the first case of the Omicron coronavirus variant, potentially challenging the country's strict zero-COVID approach.

node.title: Insurer agrees to $800 million deal in Boy Scouts bankruptcy
node.description: Century Indemnity will contribute to fund for victims of child sexual abuse in return for release from liability.

node.title: Philadelphia to check vaccine proof for bars and restaurants
node.description: Proof of vaccination is meant to decrease transmission while preventing complete shutdown of indoor dining, Mayor Jim Kenney said.

node.title: Humphrey Davies, Noted Translator of Arabic Literature, Dies at 74
node.description: He introduced numerous novels, including works by the Nobel laureate Naguib Mahfouz, to English language readers.

node.title: Ghislaine Maxwell’s Unusual Request: Allow Anonymous Defense Witnesses
node.description: Three of Ms. Maxwell’s accusers testified anonymously. Now her lawyers are asking that three defense witnesses also be able to conceal their identities.
